org.jtuples

Interface Tuple

  • All Known Implementing Classes:
    AbstractTuple, Decuple, Nonuple, Octuple, Pair, Quadruple, Quintuple, Septuple, Sextuple, Triple

    public interface Tuple
    Represents a mathematical tuple. This is a fixed-length, immutable container of elements. The number and type of its members are determined by the implementing classes.
    Author:
    Andre Santos

      • shiftLeft

        Tuple shiftLeft()
        Returns a new tuple, with the members shifted to the left by one position. This operation has a wrapping behaviour, meaning that the member that would be excluded by the shift instead occupies the new open position. For instance, calling ((1, 2, 3)).shiftLeft() would yield the tuple (2, 3, 1).
        Returns:
        a tuple shifted to the left, wrapping around

      • shiftLeft

        <V> Tuple shiftLeft(V value)
        Returns a new tuple, with the members shifted to the left by one position. The given value occupies the new open position, after shifting the original members. For instance, calling ((1, 2, 3)).shiftLeft(4) would yield the tuple (2, 3, 4).
        Type Parameters:
        V - the type of the new member to be inserted
        Parameters:
        value - the new member to be inserted
        Returns:
        a tuple shifted to the left, with the new member given

      • shiftRight

        Tuple shiftRight()
        Returns a new tuple, with the members shifted to the right by one position. This operation has a wrapping behaviour, meaning that the member that would be excluded by the shift instead occupies the new open position. For instance, calling ((1, 2, 3)).shiftRight() would yield the tuple (3, 1, 2).
        Returns:
        a tuple shifted to the right, wrapping around

      • shiftRight

        <V> Tuple shiftRight(V value)
        Returns a new tuple, with the members shifted to the right by one position. The given value occupies the new open position, after shifting the original members. For instance, calling ((1, 2, 3)).shiftRight(0) would yield the tuple (0, 1, 2).
        Type Parameters:
        V - the type of the new member to be inserted
        Parameters:
        value - the new member to be inserted
        Returns:
        a tuple shifted to the right, with the new member given

      • equals

        boolean equals(Object obj)
        Compares the specified object with this tuple for equality. Returns true if the specified object is also a tuple, the two tuples have the same arity, and all corresponding pairs of elements in the two tuples are equal. (Two elements e1 and e2 are equal if (e1 == null ? e2 == null : e1.equals(e2)).) In other words, two tuples are defined to be equal if they contain the same elements in the same order. This definition ensures that the equals method works properly across different implementations of the Tuple interface.
        Overrides:
        equals in class Object
        Parameters:
        obj - object to be compared for equality with this tuple
        Returns:
        true if the specified object is equal to this tuple

      • hashCode

        int hashCode()
        Returns the hash code value for this tuple. The hash code of a tuple is defined to be the result of the following calculation. 
        
     int hashCode = 1;
     for (Object e: tuple.asList())
         hashCode = 31*hashCode + (e==null ? 0 : e.hashCode());
        This ensures that t1.equals(t2) implies that t1.hashCode()==t2.hashCode() for any two tuples t1 and t2, as required by the general contract of Object.hashCode().
        Overrides:
        hashCode in class Object
        Returns:
        the hash code value for this tuple

      • toString

        String toString()
        Returns a string representation of this tuple. The string representation consists of a tuple of the tuple's elements in order, enclosed in parenthesis ("()"). Adjacent elements are separated by the characters ", " (comma and space). Elements are converted to strings as by String.valueOf(java.lang.Object).
        Overrides:
        toString in class Object
        Returns:
        a string representation of the tuple
